e</h2> </td> </tr> </table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say t=
hat you own some apartment buildings, want to rent out your apartments, and=
 need to figure out how much to ask. If your rents are too high, you won=E2=
=80=99t get any tenants; if they=E2=80=99re too low, you=E2=80=99ll leave m=
oney on the table. How do you do it=3F I feel like the simple model is:</p>=
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Go on StreetEasy and search for apartme=
nts that are sort of similar to yours.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">See how much they=E2=80=99re charging.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">Charge similar rates, adjusting for how much better or worse your apa=
rtments are.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If all your apartments =
are rented in two hours, you undershot, and next time you should adjust you=
r prices up; if they all languish for weeks, you overshot, and you should l=
ower your rents.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You know: Look at pu=
blic information, get a sense of the market, develop a feel for the drivers=
 of pricing, and then use your market knowledge and intuition to set prices=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This might take a lot of time, though: Y=
ou=E2=80=99d have to spend hours on StreetEasy, and you=E2=80=99d have to s=
pend months or years to develop=C2=A0a deep enough feel for the market to m=
ake you good at this. You could imagine coding up a little computer program=
 to make the process easier. Scrape StreetEasy for similar apartments, do s=
ome analysis of what characteristics drive pricing, use it to set your pric=
es, and iterate if the results are too high or too low. You could do this i=
n a simple dumb way =E2=80=94=C2=A0scrape every one-bedroom apartment in th=
e neighborhood and set your rent at the 70th percentile=3F =E2=80=94=C2=A0o=
r if you were more sophisticated you could, you know, use machine learning =
to build more refined pricing models.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Maybe=
 you don=E2=80=99t have those technical skills, though, and you might want =
to hire a computer programmer to build you a nice machine learning model to=
 scrape StreetEasy and figure out the right prices. That=E2=80=99s a little=
 inefficient too. Probably other landlords want this same product, right=3F=
 You don=E2=80=99t need to hire a programmer to build it from scratch; prob=
ably you can buy it off the shelf. Probably there=E2=80=99s one market-lead=
ing product that is really good at this, better than your own gut instinct =
and market knowledge, better than a program that you or your hired programm=
er could build. Probably the market-leading product is really good at scrap=
ing StreetEasy and Zillow and everywhere else that people list apartments f=
or rent, and it has really good algorithms for figuring out exactly what ch=
aracteristics of an apartment drive the rent up or down, so it can confiden=
tly tell you exactly what the going rate is for your apartments.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here I am saying things like =E2=80=9Cscraping Street=
Easy and Zillow,=E2=80=9D because after all apartment rental prices are=C2=
=A0<em>advertised publicly</em>, so you can go to some websites and get a s=
ense of the market rates. But it is perhaps an imperfect sense: Not every a=
partment will necessarily be listed publicly, actual leases might be negoti=
ated at higher or lower rents than what is on the website, etc.=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The market-leading product could get around this=
 problem, though, if all (or most)=C2=A0landlords used it. The product coul=
d require landlords to=C2=A0<em>input=C2=A0</em>their rental rates =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the actual prices they=E2=80=99re getting for their apartments =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and then aggregate those with all of the other landlords=E2=80=
=99 data. And then the product would have a better sense =E2=80=94=C2=A0bet=
ter than you could get from public data =E2=80=94=C2=A0of what the actual m=
arket price is, and it could be more accurate in telling landlords what pri=
ce to charge.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Would that be =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=
illegal=3F Maybe! The general rule of US antitrust law is that is illegal f=
or companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0for instance, landlords =E2=80=94=C2=A0to consp=
ire =E2=80=9Cin restraint of trade.=E2=80=9D If all the landlords got toget=
her and said =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s agree not to charge less than $3,000 a =
month for a one-bedroom,=E2=80=9D that would be illegal.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">If all the landlords got together and went around the room an=
d each one of them said =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re charging $3,000 a month for =
our one-bedrooms,=E2=80=9D that would be =E2=80=A6=C2=A0a weird meeting=3F =
Like I=E2=80=99d be pretty nervous going to that meeting=3F Presumably that=
 meeting is not being held for purely informational purposes; presumably te=
lling your competitors =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re charging $3,000 a month=E2=80=
=9D is a somewhat subtle way to communicate =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s not char=
ge less.=E2=80=9D It doesn=E2=80=99t have to mean that, though. You could g=
o to that meeting and be like =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re charging $2,700 a mont=
h to win business from all of you, nyah nyah nyah,=E2=80=9D and everyone el=
se could give you dirty looks and you could be fine with it.=C2=A0You could=
 use information about your competitors=E2=80=99 prices to be=C2=A0<em>more=
 competitive</em>.=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0<em>quite=C2=A0</em>an agreem=
ent to keep prices high, but it looks suspicious.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">You don=E2=80=99t need a meeting.=C2=A0If all the landlords sent the=
